summary.seg: This Gospel lectionary, probably copied in the second half of the 12th century, belongs to the fuller of the two main types, giving lections for weekdays as well as Saturdays and Sundays, except in Lent. It is a high-quality production, richly ornamented with extensive use of gold in its headpieces, its initial letters and for the text of headings and other rubrics regarding the lections. At one point a portion of a folio which would have contained a major headpiece (f. 104r) is missing, and may have been deliberately cut out for separate sale. Many entire folios have also been lost, and in the early part of the manuscript many of the surviving folios have been rebound in the wrong order.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of variable thickness and medium quality.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-iii] + 1-6, 8-9, 7, 10-165 + [iv-vi], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right and recto, lower left.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 30 quires, of which one is a single bifolio and the rest were probably quaternia. Due to the loss of many folios, this reconstruction is conjectural in places. As indicated below, a number of folios have been bound out of order. The foliation numbers f. 7 according to its proper placement in the sequence of the text rather than its current location, but other misplaced folios are numbered by their current sequence. A number of original quires have been lost, preceding the present Quires 1, 3, 5, 13, 14, 16 and 21.

collation.signatures: There are modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals at the beginning of each quire, in pencil, recto, lower right (1-27). There are various errors in this numbering.

supportDesc.condition: There have been significant losses from the edges of ff. 7, 118-119, 157 and 164-165, which have been repaired with parchment patches. There is minor wear and tear to the edges of some other folios, occasional creasing, some water staining, drops of wax and areas of dirt. Paint from some of the ornament has been transferred to the facing page.

layoutDesc.layout:
Two columns of 24 lines. 212 160
Piercing survives in all three margins. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 44C2. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The text was copied in mixed minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in black ink, with modest variation in letter size. There is occasional modest flourishing of tails into the lower margin.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings only at the end of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is frequent decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra. The circumflex appears above breathings and is often expanded there. The double grave accent is in use.

Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, middle comma, question mark and full stop. Middle and upper points are occasionally marked in red ink, and on other occasions are very often accompanied by a cross in red ink.
Lection headings and other rubric were written in Alexandrine majuscule script in red ink and gilded.

decoDesc.decoNote: Pylai in red, blue, green and white paint and gold precede the beginning of the menologion on f. 119r and the beginning of the eothina on f. 157r. A similar headpiece probably originally preceded the beginning of the weeks on f. 104r, but appears to have been deliberately cut out. The opening folios of other major sections of the synaxarion have been lost, but may be supposed to have received similar ornament. Narrow bands of ornament in gold, sometimes with red and blue paint infill, mark the beginning or end of some months of the menologion and miscellaneous texts (e.g. ff. 58v, 142v, 145v, 151v, 153r).
Each lection begins with an ornamented initial, sometimes in gold alone, usually outlined in red ink which has been gilded, with red, blue, green and white paint infill.

Lection headings and rubrics were written in red ink and gilded. Most of the rubrics in the last few folios (ff. 159v-165r) lack gilding, but traces of gold in places suggest that this is due to the loss of the original gilding rather than its original omission.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, lection notes have been included in the margins.
There are occasional pen-trials or doodles (e.g ff. 71r).
There is a note of ownership by Angelos Staka on f. 1r: Κτῆμα τοῦ Ἀγγελῆ Κ. Στάκα.

binding.p: 19th-century binding, hollow back, sewn with cord on recessed supports, with red velvet covering over millboards, parchment pastedowns.
binding.condition: Both endbands are partially split, in line with a preferential opening between ff. 72-73.

physDesc.accMat: There are separate sewn parchment endleaves, belonging to the present binding. There is a bookplate indicating ownership by Frank McClean on the left pastedown, along with a printed description of the manuscript and a brief note of its content and date in pencil. A loose slip of paper with a brief description, clipped from the Sotheby's sale catalogue, is inserted inside the left board.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied in the second half of the 12th century, as suggested by the style of script.

provenance.p: Owned by Angelos Staka Staka, Angelos , as indicated by the note on f. 1r.
Owned by the historian Henry White (1812-1880) White, Henry, 1812-1880 .
Purchased by the astronomer and collector Frank McClean (1837-1904) McClean, F. (Frank), 1837-1904 in the auction of the White collection at Sotheby's in April 1902 (lot 849).

history.acquisition: Bequeathed to the Fitzwilliam Museum by McClean, together with the rest of his collection, in 1904.
